l><li>In 2015, The 9th/12th Royal Lancers and The Queens Lancers formed The Royal Lancers on amalgamation, prior to this the Regiments are counted separately for clarity and The Royal Lancers figures will be N/A as the Regiment was not yet formed.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>The 1 Royal Tank Regiment (RTR) and 2RTR formed under the Royal Tank Regiment on amalgamation in 2015.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Figures have been rounded to 10 for presentational purposes; numbers ending in &quot;5&quot; have been rounded to the nearest multiple of 20 to prevent systematic bias. Totals and sub-totals have been rounded separately and so may not appear to be the sum of their parts. “-” denotes zero or rounded to zero.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-10-30T16:41:53.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992698/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992698/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-22","Army: Discharges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many people have left the Army service (a) voluntarily, (b) as a result of time expired and (c) for other reasons by regiment in each year from 2010.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","182140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992699","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-10-26","<p>The Confidential Employer and Families Survey on Reserves, Family and Work (as part of the Future Reserves Research Programme (FRRP)) was placed onto the Defence Connect and Defence Gateway, the Ministry of Defence's (MOD) on-line platforms for Defence Personnel. The survey was launched on 2 March 2018 with a blog that was viewed by 2,814 people and re-blogged into around 250 Reservist pages across the three Services. The survey was available continuously over an 8-week period, with Defence Connect and Defence Gateway viewed around 1,879,000 and 871,000 times respectively during that time.</p><p>The survey was undertaken by a consortium of university researchers and disseminated by the Army on behalf of all three Services. The MOD has been advised that there were around 400 responses to the survey. It is expected that the results of the survey will be shared through the FRRP website before the end of the year.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","181199 ; 181200 ; 181201 ; 181202","2018-10-26T09:39:46.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992699/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992699/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-22","Reserve Forces: Surveys","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that information on the survey on negotiating civilian and military life was disseminated to Army Reservists.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","182141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992700","Home Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>The National County Lines Working Group brings together a range of agencies including law enforcement to assess the trends in county lines and action that should be taken. This ensures that we are up to date on the latest developments involving county lines reported by the police and National Crime Agency.</p><p>In June this year, the Home Secretary announced funding of £1.38m to support a new national police capability to tackle gang related activity on social media which will be operational shortly. Representatives from Google and Facebook also attended a meeting of the Serious Violence Taskforce chaired by the Home Secretary in June to present the action they are taking to tackle gang related content online.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","182082","2018-10-25T16:15:45.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992700/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992700/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of the use of encrypted messaging apps by people involved in county lines drugs dealing.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","182081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992701","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) has a duty to protect public funds and an obligation to ensure that, overpaid benefit payments are recovered in accordance with the appropriate social security legislation.</p><p> </p><p>DWP does not routinely publish prosecution statistics and the specific information requested is not available at a granular level. This could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Carers Allowance claimants would only be deemed to have been overpaid if their earnings exceeded the earnings threshold after allowable deductions have been taken into account.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-10-25T09:11:33.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992701/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992701/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Carer's Allowance: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many prosecutions for fraud of Carers Allowance there has been as a result of earnings exceeding the threshold by (a) less than 10 per cent, (b) less than 20 percent, (c) less than 10 per cent after deductions and (d) less than 20 per cent  after deductions in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Ruth George","High Peak","Ruth George","182242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992702","Department for Education","false","2018-10-30","<p>The department have not made any formal assessment of this report. We are continuing to improve standards on literacy and to support schools and parents on special educational needs and disabilities (SEND) including dyslexia.</p><p> </p><p>Schools are required under the Children and Families Act (2014) and the accompanying SEND Code of Practice to identify and address the special educational needs (SEN) of the pupils or students they support. Maintained schools are given notional SEN budgets and should use this to pay for support to children with dyslexia where required. Schools must use their best endeavours to make sure that a child with SEN gets the support they need - this means doing everything they can to meet children and young people’s SEN.</p><p> </p><p>The Equality Act (2010) is clear that a person (P) has a disability if - (a) P has a physical or mental impairment, and (b) the impairment has a substantial and long-term adverse effect on P's ability to carry out normal day-to-day activities. All schools have duties under the Equality Act (2010) towards individual disabled children and young people.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","182143 ; 182888","2018-10-30T13:34:57.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992702/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992702/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-22","Special Educational Needs: Dyslexia ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if he will make an assessment of the accuracy of the statement by Warwickshire County Council in its document, Teaching Children & Young People with Literacy Difficulties Practice Guidance February 2018, on advice to parents in relation to the status of dyslexia as a disability that is not fully recognised in UK law.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","182142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992703","Department for Education","false","2018-10-30","<p>The department have not made any formal assessment of this report. We are continuing to improve standards on literacy and to support schools and parents on special educational needs and disabilities (SEND) including dyslexia.</p><p> </p><p>Schools are required under the Children and Families Act (2014) and the accompanying SEND Code of Practice to identify and address the special educational needs (SEN) of the pupils or students they support. Maintained schools are given notional SEN budgets and should use this to pay for support to children with dyslexia where required. Schools must use their best endeavours to make sure that a child with SEN gets the support they need - this means doing everything they can to meet children and young people’s SEN.</p><p> </p><p>The Equality Act (2010) is clear that a person (P) has a disability if - (a) P has a physical or mental impairment, and (b) the impairment has a substantial and long-term adverse effect on P's ability to carry out normal day-to-day activities. All schools have duties under the Equality Act (2010) towards individual disabled children and young people.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","182142 ; 182888","2018-10-30T13:34:57.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992703/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992703/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-22","Special Educational Needs: Dyslexia ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the document entitled, Teaching Children & Young People with Literacy Difficulties Practice Guidance February 2018, published by Warwickshire County Council, if he will make an assessment of the effect on students with Dyslexia of not providing those students with special support except in extreme circumstances.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","182143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992704","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-30","<p>(a) The FCO owns 7 vehicles for use at the British Embassy in Paris.</p><p>(b) The FCO owns 67 vehicles for use by a number of government departments at the British High Commission in Nairobi. These form a transport pool, used by staff from all departments (including the FCO, DfID and DIT) who have signed up to and paid to use the vehicles. A number of these are technical works vehicles used for the secure transportation of building maintenance equipment and water delivery.</p><p>(c) The FCO owns 23 vehicles for use at the British Embassy in Riyadh.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-30T15:30:33.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992704/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992704/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Diplomatic Service: Official Cars","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many cars owned by his Department there are at the British Embassy in (a) Paris, (b) Nairobi and (c) Riyadh.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","182096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992705","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-10-29","<p>In financial year 2017-2018 the FCO posts of Paris, Nairobi and Riyadh spent the following on hospitality:</p><ol><li>Paris: £270,883.83</li><li>Nairobi: £154,408.84</li><li>Riyadh: £128,550.61</li></ol>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2018-10-29T15:29:59.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992705/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992705/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-10-22","Diplomatic Service: Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much was spent on hospitality by the British Ambassador to (a) Paris (b) Nairobi and (c) Riyadh in the financial year 2017-2018.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","182097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992706","Home Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>The National County Lines Working Group brings together a range of agencies including law enforcement to assess the trends in county lines and action that should be taken. This ensures that we are up to date on the latest developments involving county lines reported by the police and National Crime Agency.</p><p>In June this year, the Home Secretary announced funding of £1.38m to support a new national police capability to tackle gang related activity on social media which will be operational shortly. Representatives from Google and Facebook also attended a meeting of the Serious Violence Taskforce chaired by the Home Secretary in June to present the action they are taking to tackle gang related content online.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins","182081","2018-10-25T16:15:45.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992706/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992706/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Drugs: Organised Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent meetings (a) he and (b) his officials have had with representatives of (i) Facebook/Instagram/WhatsApp, (ii) Kik Messenger, (iii) Snapchat, (iv) Telegram, (v) Viber, (vi) Wickr and (vii) other social media and messenger sites on the use of their encrypted messaging apps for county lines drugs dealing.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","182082"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992707","Home Office","false","2018-10-30","<p>The number of illegal workers encountered during visits within the LE postcode area, where civil penalties were issued between 1 January 2017 to 31 December 2017 was 57</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-10-30T16:34:12.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992707/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992707/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Undocumented Workers: Leicester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people in Leicester were working illegally between January 2017 and January 2018.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","182098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992708","Home Office","false","2018-10-30","<p>The total value of civil penalties issued between 1 January 2017 to 31 December 2017 where illegal workers were encountered during visits within (a) London Boroughs was £9.5m and (b) South East England (not including London Boroughs) was £7m.</p><p>Please note all figures are for penalties levied at the initial decision stage which may be reduced, cancelled, increased or reissued at the objection or appeal stage.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-10-30T16:36:58.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992708/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992708/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Undocumented Workers: Greater London and South East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the value of penalties issued to employers of illegal workers was in (a) London and (b) the South East between January 2017 and January 2018.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","182099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992709","Home Office","false","2018-10-30","<p>A total of 1,818 penalty notices have been served between 1 January 2018 and 30 September 2018.*</p><p>*This relates to notices served at the point of detection informing a driver/haulier that they are potentially liable for a penalty.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-10-30T16:53:19.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992709/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992709/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Undocumented Migrants: Fixed Penalties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many penalty notices on drivers and hauliers carrying illegal entrants have been issued since January 2018.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","182100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992710","Home Office","false","2018-10-30","<p>A total of £951,336 has been recovered between 1 January 2018 and 30 September 2018.*</p><p>*Note the monies recovered do not directly relate to the penalty notices served during the same period.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-10-30T16:55:41.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992710/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992710/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Undocumented Migrants: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much revenue has accrued to the public purse from penalties on British drivers and hauliers carrying clandestine illegal entrants in 2018.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","182101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992711","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-30","<p>The Government has appointed Byron Davies as its first ever General Aviation Champion, in order to identify a network of strategically important airfields and to help the future development of the general aviation sector. He is being assisted by York Aviation, which the Department has commissioned to carry out research on airfields of strategic significance. The Government intends to publish his report and the York Aviation report alongside the Aviation Strategy Green Paper later this year. The Government will only be able to take decisions on implementing a general aviation strategic network once the General Aviation Champion has made his recommendations and consultation has concluded on the Aviation Strategy Green Paper.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","182244","2018-10-30T16:01:51.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992711/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992711/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's news story, Government champion raises profile for general aviation, published on 7 February 2018, when his Department plans to publish the York Aviation report on proposals for a strategic network for general aviation airfields.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","182243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992712","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-30","<p>The Government has appointed Byron Davies as its first ever General Aviation Champion, in order to identify a network of strategically important airfields and to help the future development of the general aviation sector. He is being assisted by York Aviation, which the Department has commissioned to carry out research on airfields of strategic significance. The Government intends to publish his report and the York Aviation report alongside the Aviation Strategy Green Paper later this year. The Government will only be able to take decisions on implementing a general aviation strategic network once the General Aviation Champion has made his recommendations and consultation has concluded on the Aviation Strategy Green Paper.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","182243","2018-10-30T16:01:51.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992712/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992712/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his Department's news story, Government champion raises profile for general aviation, published on 7 February 2018, when he plans to implement the general aviation strategic network.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","182244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992713","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-30","<p>The Department for Transport has published no guidance on the commercial development of general aviation airfields. The development of such airfields is a matter for their owners and operators, within national planning policy, including the revised National Planning Policy Framework published on 24 July 2018.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-30T16:31:07.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992713/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992713/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance his Department provides on the commercial development of general aviation airfields.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","182245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992714","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-25","<p>Officials are in continuous discussion with HGV manufacturers and relevant trade associations about how different vehicle designs could improve safety for pedestrians and cyclists. These cover a range of options, including safer vehicle fronts, mirrors, better direct vision, camera monitoring systems, other detection or warning devices, side under-run guards and electronic safety aids such as advanced emergency braking systems.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-25T10:14:18.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992714/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992714/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Large Goods Vehicles: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with heavy goods vehicle manufacturers on altering the designs of vehicles to improve safety on roads for pedestrians and cyclists; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","182075"
