p></td><td><p>50%</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>3%</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>20%</p></td><td><p>52</p></td><td><p>49%</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>5%</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>108</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td><td><p>59</p></td><td><p>55%</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>112</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>58</p></td><td><p>52%</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4%</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>4%</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: DfT STATS19</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="10"><p><ol><li>Proportions would not add up to 100% in a year as a fatal road accident involving a pedal cyclist can also involve none other, one other or multiple vehicles in the road accident.</li></ol></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>On 18 October the Department published a summary of the 14,000 responses received to its Call for Evidence on cycling and walking safety, including issues relating to large vehicles. We have recently announced a number of activities to improve the safety, and perception of safety, of cycling and walking: tailored cycle training for driving instructors, support for police in tackling unsafe “close passing”, an update to the National Standard for Cycle Training and, most recently, a review of the Highway Code to include overtaking and opening vehicle doors.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will publish its full response to the Call for Evidence in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","182076","2018-10-25T12:10:06.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992716/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992716/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Cycling: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many road accidents with cyclists there were in each of the last ten years; how many of those accidents were fatal; how many and what proportion of those fatal accidents involved (a) heavy goods vehicles, (b) cars, (c) other cyclists and (d) pedestrians; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","182077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992717","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-30","<p>The Department for Transport has not commissioned any recent research in this area but it has monitored research commissioned by other bodies, including Transport for London and the European Commission.</p><p> </p><p>Officials have liaised with Transport for London on their proposals to improve the design of heavy goods vehicle cabs to allow the driver a better view, especially on the passenger side. The Government supported the notification of the technical requirements to the European Commission and is optimistic that these measures will come into force for certain large goods vehicles entering London from October 2019. We are also supporting measures under the European Commission’s Third Mobility Package to improve further the protection of pedestrians and cyclists.</p><p> </p><p>The European Commission has carried out research to reduce the danger of HGV vehicle fronts in the context of vulnerable road users. We anticipate final proposals based upon this research to be published by the end of the year.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-30T15:48:36.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992717/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992717/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Large Goods Vehicles: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what research he has commissioned on the design of heavy goods vehicles to determine what alterations could be made to improve road safety for cyclists and pedestrians; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","182078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992718","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-25","<p>Where further medical evidence is required, it will be requested directly from a Doctor or Healthcare worker. In the majority of cases, further medical evidence will be requested by a Health Professional who is directly involved with the case. DWP do not hold this level of Management Information across all benefits.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-10-25T09:17:35.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992718/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992718/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times her Department has contacted the doctor or healthcare worker of a benefits claimant to request medical evidence for their claim in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","182086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992719","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-25","<p>Internal audit, as carried out by the suppliers, is one element of the supplier quality management regime, which is subject to ongoing review. Information on the internal audit of our Assessment Providers is not a contractual MI requirement and the collective information you have requested is not available.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-10-25T14:11:23.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992719/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992719/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many internal audits of claimant health assessments were carried out by the organisations responsible for (a) work capability and (b) personal independence payment assessments in each year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Marion Fellows","Motherwell and Wishaw","Marion Fellows","182246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992720","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-25","<p>BEIS engages regularly with UK based businesses and trade associations across a range of sectors including consumer goods. We understand the concerns of these businesses about retaining frictionless trade and want all manufacturers across the UK, including in West Yorkshire, to thrive now and in the future.</p><p> </p><p>To help us engage effectively, we have set up sector-specific EU Exit panels. The first consumer goods panel will be taking place in early November and all consumer goods activity in the UK, including furniture manufacturing, is represented.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has been clear that the best outcome is for the UK to leave the EU with a deal and why, following months of intensive work and detailed discussions, we proposed a third option for our future economic relationship, based on the frictionless trade in goods.</p><p> </p><p>At March European Council, the UK and EU agreed that during the implementation period, the UK would be treated as a Member State for the purposes of international agreements, including trade agreements.</p><p> </p><p>This provides certainty and confidence for business that there will be no disruption to existing relationships underpinned by international agreements as we move into the Implementation Period.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-10-25T13:46:53.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992720/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992720/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-22","Furniture: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the potential effect on the operations of bed manufacturers in (a) West Yorkshire and (b) the rest of the UK of leaving the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","182247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992721","Department for Education","false","2018-10-25","<p>Of the mainstream and special free schools opened since September 2017, 21 have nursery provision, and a further nine have plans for nursery provision. These figures are broken down in the attached table.</p><p><br>Of the 20 primary schools approved by the department during the same period, 13 have plans for nursery provision. This includes 11 (of 18) schools approved following local authority-run competitions (as required by Section 6A of the Education and Inspection Act 2006) and 2 (of 2) special primary schools approved through the department’s special free school application wave. These figures relate to schools that have exclusively primary-aged pupils.</p><p>As local authorities (LA) are responsible for approving LA maintained schools, we do not hold information on the number of LA maintained schools approved in this period.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-10-25T16:47:31.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992721/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992721/answer","182248_attachment.doc","182248_attachment.doc","New_schools_with_nursery_provision_since_2017","New_schools_with_nursery_provision_since_2017","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992721/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-22","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 19 October 2018 to Question 179290, how many mainstream and special (a) free schools that have opened since September 2017 (i) have or (ii) have plans for nursery provision and (b) primary schools that have been approved since that date have plans for nursery provision.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","182248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992722","Treasury","false","2018-10-26","<p>The UK’s financial services regulators operate secondment programmes to financial services firms, regulatory bodies and institutions – including those in the EU and rest of the world - and do so for various reasons.</p><p> </p><p>The number of personnel seconded and the purpose for doing so is a matter for the independent regulators.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-10-26T11:10:23.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992722/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992722/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-22","Financial Services: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many personnel from each financial sector regulator for which he is responsible have been seconded and for what purpose to a financial regulator elsewhere in the EU.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Sir Bernard Jenkin","182073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992723","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-10-30","<p>As the Prime Minister said on Monday 22 October, following discussions with Spain and in close cooperation with the Government of Gibraltar, we have developed a protocol and set of underlying memoranda relating to Gibraltar. As set out in our White Paper, we will be seeking a future relationship for Gibraltar which appropriately reflects the particular characteristics and needs of the area, taking account of Gibraltar’s deep existing relationship with the EU.</p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2018-10-30T13:25:05.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992723/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992723/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-10-22","Gibraltar: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assurances have been given to the Government of Gibraltar on the (a) withdrawal agreement that the UK is negotiating with the EU and (b) framework for the UK's future relationship with the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Sir Bernard Jenkin","182074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992724","Treasury","false","2018-10-25","<p>The lease for the HMRC office in Cumbernauld, Accounts Office, ends in April 2021. HMRC has the option to extend the lease to allow it to remain in the property until the Glasgow Regional Centre opens.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","182250","2018-10-25T14:53:22.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992724/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992724/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-22","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the lease is due to end on the HMRC office in Cumbernauld.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","182249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992725","Treasury","false","2018-10-25","<p>The lease for the HMRC office in Cumbernauld, Accounts Office, ends in April 2021. HMRC has the option to extend the lease to allow it to remain in the property until the Glasgow Regional Centre opens.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","182249","2018-10-25T14:53:22.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992725/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992725/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-22","Revenue and Customs: Cumbernauld","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the lease on the HMRC office in Cumbernauld includes an option to extend its duration.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","182250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992726","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-25","<p>We shall give further consideration to our human rights legal framework when the process of leaving the EU concludes. We will consult fully on proposals in the full knowledge of the new constitutional landscape.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's absolute priority remains the restoration of devolved government in Northern Ireland, in part, so that the people of Northern Ireland, and locally elected representatives, can decide what is right for Northern Ireland on sensitive devolved issues.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-10-25T15:37:56.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992726/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992726/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-22","Bill of Rights: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions he plans to have and with whom in the absence of the Northern Ireland Executive on a UK-wide Bill of Rights.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","182102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992727","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Council welcomes the opportunity to hold meetings across the country. The policy areas under consideration are largely devolved. However the Council works closely with the Devolved Administrations where appropriate and officials from the Devolved Administrations are invited to attend Council meetings. The majority of Council members also work across the UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-10-25T16:18:32.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992727/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992727/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-10-22","Arts: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if he will discuss with the Creative Industries Council its meeting in future in Northern Ireland to ensure that creative industries policies are developed in the Province.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","182103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992728","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-10-25","<p>No.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-10-25T09:59:42.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992728/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992728/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-22","Moorland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will support an independent inquiry into the sustainability and legality of grouse moor management in England.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","182251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992729","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-10-25","<p>This information is not centrally held.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-10-25T11:28:48.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992729/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992729/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-22","Social Services: Bureaucracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care,  if he will make an assessment of the average proportion of the working week that social workers spend completing paperwork and other follow-up administrative procedures relating to the main part of their employment.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","182104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992730","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-25","<p>The UK supports the principle of a new financing mechanism for education led by the multilateral development banks to target the financing gap in lower middle income countries. Once the technical design work has been concluded by the Education Commission and the multilateral development banks I will set out the UK’s final position.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","182253","2018-10-25T16:06:49.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992730/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992730/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-22","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate she has made of the amount of Official Development Assistance to be allocated by her Department to the International Financing Facility for Education.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","182252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992731","Department for International Development","false","2018-10-25","<p>The UK supports the principle of a new financing mechanism for education led by the multilateral development banks to target the financing gap in lower middle income countries. Once the technical design work has been concluded by the Education Commission and the multilateral development banks I will set out the UK’s final position.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","182252","2018-10-25T16:06:49.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992731/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992731/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-10-22","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, when she plans to announce the Government's financial commitment to the International Financing Facility for Education.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","182253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992732","Department for Education","false","2018-10-25","<p>The consultation referred to, which ran from 10 April 2018 to 2 July 2018, included draft guidance on elective home education which is intended to replace that currently published by the department. It was open to any member of the public, including parents educating their children at home, and the responses received are currently being considered before the new guidance document is published in its final form.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-10-25T16:19:12.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992732/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992732/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-22","Home Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the consultation, Home Education - Call for Evidence and revised DfE guidance, what plans her Department has to consult the with home education community in the development of guidelines for home education.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","182144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992733","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-25","<p>These clauses do not prevent the contracting bodies from making statements critical of government policy or politicians, and certainly do not prevent whistle-blowing (as this would be unlawful). They are designed to protect government, to ensure that contractors adhere to good working practices and do not engage in activities that will bring the Authority into disrepute or otherwise harm the confidence of the public in Government.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-10-25T15:10:51.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992733/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992733/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Department for Work and Pensions: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of contracts between her Department and charities include a gagging clause; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","182145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992734","Department for Transport","false","2018-10-25","<p>Public transport links will be improved by the commitment in the new Wales and Borders franchise let by the Welsh Government to improve service frequency on this line, with refurbished trains, from 2021. In addition, the Department for Transport is providing the necessary funding to develop a strategic outline business case for improvements to rail journey times between Wrexham and Bidston.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-10-25T13:28:27.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992734/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992734/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-10-22","Railways: Deeside Industrial Park","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to improve public transport links between Birkenhead and the Deeside Industrial Park.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","182105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992735","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-30","<p>We welcome the work that the Social Metrics Commission has done. Measuring poverty is complex, and this report offers further insight into that complexity. From discussions with SMC they acknowledge that further work needs to be done (particularly around data availability and quality). We will carefully consider their recommendations and the detail behind the methodology they have employed when this has been made available.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-10-30T11:53:41.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992735/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992735/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of the recommendations in the report, A new measure of poverty for the UK, published by the Social Metrics Commission in September 2018.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992736","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-30","<p>We have invited local authorities to disclose any additional costs that they have encountered associated with Universal Credit, and will consider the evidence under the new burdens funding policy.</p><p> </p><p>One local authority has requested additional funding and we are currently awaiting a completed additional costs claim form from them.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-10-30T18:01:06.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992736/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992736/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether her Department has received representations from representatives of local authorities on the reimbursement of the additional costs of administering universal credit.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992737","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-12-11","<p>We have not made an assessment.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit targets resources towards reducing the number of workless households, by increasing the incentive for at least one member of the household to enter work. Compared to children from working families, children who grow up in workless families are almost twice as likely to not reach the expected attainment level at all stages of their education, and are also more likely to be workless themselves in adult life. Helping at least one person into work could help break the cycle of worklessness in a family.</p><p> </p><p>As announced at Autumn Budget 2018, on 29 October 2018, work allowances will be increased by £1000 a year from April 2019. This increase for working parents and people with disabilities, means 2.4 million households will be up to £630 better off per year, in a package worth £1.7bn by 2023/24.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-12-11T10:28:12.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992737/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992737/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of creating a work allowance for second earners as part of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992738","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-30","<p>The lower rates for younger claimants who are under the age of 25 years reflects the fact that they are more likely to live in someone else's household and have lower living costs and lower earnings expectations. This also reinforces the stronger work incentives that Universal Credit creates for this age group.</p><p> </p><p>Many claimants will have higher entitlements under Universal Credit but for those who do not, anyone on existing benefits or tax credits whose circumstances remain the same will not lose out in cash terms when claiming Universal Credit, as part of the managed migration process. These claimants will be given transitional protection to avoid cash loss at the point of change.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit is more generous in terms of childcare costs with an increased level of support for childcare costs from 70 per cent in legacy benefits, to 85 per cent within Universal Credit. This means that working families claiming Universal Credit can reclaim up to 85 per cent of their eligible childcare costs each month, up to a maximum of £646.35 for one child and £1,108.04 for two or more children. Since February 2018, Universal Credit claimants have been able to upload digital copies of their childcare cost receipts or invoices through their online Universal Credit account, which makes this process easier.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit also includes support for housing costs, children and support for disabled people and carers.</p><p><strong>__________________________________________________________________________</strong></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-10-30T17:56:46.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992738/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992738/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Universal Credit: Lone Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons lone parents under 25 years old will no longer be entitled to receive the higher rate of personal allowance under universal credit.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992739","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-30","<p>We can provide an estimate based on households claiming UC by matching the UC household dataset (which contains information about family type), with the people on UC dataset (which contains information about age). The table gives the estimated total number of households on UC and those occupied by single parents under the age of 25 in June 2018. The notes should be read in conjunction with the information provided in the table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Estimated number of total households on Universal Credit and those occupied by single parents under the age of 25, Great Britain, June 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of households</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>883,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Single parents aged under 25</p></td><td><p>34,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Source:</strong> Universal Credit household dataset <strong>and</strong> people on Universal Credit dataset</p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ol><li>The figures are derived from unpublished information and have not been quality assured to National Statistics or Official Statistics publication standard.</li><li>Figures have been rounded to the nearest thousand. Individual figures may not add up to the total due to rounding.</li><li>A count date of the second Thursday of the month is used when calculating the statistics for the people and households on Universal Credit.</li><li>The figure for households occupied by single parents has been deduced where the household has a family type of ‘single with child dependent(s)’.</li><li>Further information on the background and methodology can be accessed here: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/739399/universal-credit-statistics-background-methodology.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/739399/universal-credit-statistics-background-methodology.pdf</a></li><li>It has not been possible to determine the age of approximately 8,000 single parent households</li></ol>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-10-30T18:03:12.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992739/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992739/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Universal Credit: Lone Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of universal credit claimants are lone parents under 25.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992740","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-12-03","<p>Implicit Consent is usually used when a third party wants to check the progress of a claim or assist a customer with a question about their entitlement. For more vulnerable claimants unable to mange their own affairs, an appointee or corporate acting body will make the claim on their behalf. If implicit consent was used to make a new claim there is no specific area that the details are held on the legacy system.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-12-03T16:30:22.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992740/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992740/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of claimants used implicit consent to make a benefits claim under the legacy system.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992741","Treasury","false","2018-10-30","<p>As with other legacy benefits, the government is considering the position of tax credit claimants who receive historical ESA payments from DWP.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-10-30T14:53:20.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992741/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992741/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-22","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether people in receipt of back-payments for ESA are also entitled to receive back-payments for tax credits.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992742","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-30","<p>This exercise is to correct historic errors in Employment and Support Allowance and ensure arrears due are paid in line with primary legislation.</p><p>Legacy benefits is the term used for benefits migrating to Universal Credit – these are income-related Employment and Support Allowance, Income-Based Jobseekers Allowance, Income Support, Housing Benefits, Child and Working Tax Credits.</p><p>Where the Department administers these benefits we are ensuring that arrears due, as a result of these historic errors, are made to claimants in line with primary legislation. For benefits administered outside of the Department such as Tax Credits, eligibility is determined by the relevant authority/department.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-10-30T10:21:02.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992742/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992742/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether people in receipt of back-payments for employment support allowance will also be in receipt of back-payments for other legacy benefits.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","182261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992743","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-25","<p>Work offers people the best opportunity to get out of poverty. Children of lone parent workless families are around 4 times more likely to be in poverty than those where their parent works full time. We are helping lone parents with the biggest challenges they face. Universal Credit is a modern welfare system where work always pays. Since April 2016, the Universal Credit childcare element covers up to 85% of eligible costs, compared with 70% in the legacy tax credits system. Lone parents are also no longer incentivised to work just 16 hours, unlike the legacy system. National Statistics show there are 100k fewer children of lone parents in absolute poverty than 2010.</p><p>We welcome the work that the Social Metrics Commission has done. Measuring poverty is complex, and this report offers further insight into that complexity and the additional measures that can be taken into consideration. From discussions with SMC they acknowledge that further work needs to be done (particularly around data availability and quality). We will carefully consider their recommendations and the detail behind the methodology they have employed when this has been made available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-10-25T15:03:06.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992743/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992743/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Poverty: Lone Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the report by the Social Metrics Commission, A new measure of poverty in the UK, published in September 2018, what steps her Department is taking to support single parent families that live in poverty.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","182262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992744","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-10-25","<p>The causes of violence in prison are complex, but we know that the skills and availability of staff play a critical role in maintaining order. We have invested in over 3,000 additional staff in order to deliver consistent, purposeful regimes, and providing training to both new and existing staff to equip them to take on the new key worker role, in which they will provide more effective challenge and support to prisoners.</p><p> </p><p>Our prison staff work incredibly hard and we are under no illusions about the challenges they face. We are taking urgent action to make prisons safer, and assaults on our staff will never be tolerated. That is why we are working with the Police and Crown Prosecution Service to ensure successful prosecutions of those who assault them. It is also why the Government supported the recently passed Assaults on Emergency Workers (Offences) Act, which increases sentences for those who attack emergency workers, including prison officers.</p><p> </p><p>We are taking further measures to protect our staff, including investing in 5,600 body-worn cameras and in rigid-bar handcuffs. Early next year we will begin to equip every prison officer in the adult male prison estate with PAVA incapacitant spray. PAVA can help to prevent serious harm to staff and prisoners alike, as well as being a tool to persuade prisoners in the act of violence to stop. It will be deployed only in prisons that have rolled out key workers, and in which staff have been properly trained.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-10-25T13:15:26.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992744/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992744/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-22","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of reductions in the number of (a) prison officers and (b) experienced prison officers on the level of violence in prisons.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","182263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992745","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-10-25","<p>This information is not readily available and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-10-25T15:31:55.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992745/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992745/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-22","Universal Credit: Depressive Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people claimants of universal credit with a diagnosis of depression (a) not receive an award after their initial assessment and (b) received an award after tribunal.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","182264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992746","Department for Education","false","2018-10-25","<p>Our new criteria for free school meals eligibility are forecast to increase the number of children benefiting from this vital benefit by 2022, compared to under the previous benefits system. In addition, our transitional protections will mean that all children currently receiving a free meal will continue to do so.</p><p>In February, the government published an updated equality analysis on the criteria following a public consultation. Our overall assessment was that we expect children with a special educational need or disability, pupils attending schools with no religious character, and children from certain ethnic groups to benefit more than others from the estimated increase in the size of the free school meal cohort. These children were identified as more likely to benefit from the new criteria because they are considered more likely to come from households with earnings below the new eligibility threshold. We did not have evidence to suggest there will be any negative impact on children with other protected characteristics.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-10-25T16:26:25.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992746/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992746/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-22","Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of the changes to the eligibility criteria for free school meals on the number of families living in poverty.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","182265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992747","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) has contracts for the provision of services with the following suppliers:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><ol><li>Aramark</li><li>Arcadis (Formerly EC Harris)</li><li>BT</li><li>Capital Works</li><li>Clarity Travel</li><li>Criticall Limited</li><li>Egress Switch</li><li>Engie</li><li>HRG Travel</li><li>ITRS (Internet Research and Training Services</li><li>Marsh</li><li>Microsoft</li><li>Minerva Elite Performance Ltd</li><li>Office Labs</li><li>Oracle</li><li>RBS</li><li>Restore (previously TNT)</li><li>SSCL</li><li>Swiss Post Solutions</li><li>UK SBS</li><li>Westminster City Council</li></ol></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>BEIS do not hold records on how many people are employed on each contract. Suppliers are responsible for their own resource allocation on a contract.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-10-25T13:48:38.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992747/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992747/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-22","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Contracts for Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which companies his Department has contracted for the provision of departmental services; and how many staff are employed under those contracts by those companies.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","182266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992748","Home Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Home Office collects data on the number of crimes recorded by the police in England and Wales but it is not possible to separately identify assaults against shopkeepers or robberies of shops from the data centrally held.</p><p>Statistics on all assaults and of robberies of business property are published quarterly by the Office for National Statistics (ONS). The latest figures, which contain time series from April 2002 to June 2018, can be accessed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables</a></p><p>The Home Office’s Commercial Victimisation Survey provides estimates of the volume of crime experienced by business premises including in the Wholesale and Retail sector. The survey is able to estimate the number of assaults and threats and the number of robberies experienced by businesses in that sector but the sample size is not large enough to provide separate estimates of the number of assaults against shopkeepers or the proportion of robberies in which a weapon has been used. The latest results from the CVS can be accessed here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/crime-against-businesses-findings-from-the-2017-commercial-victimisation-survey</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","182147","2018-10-25T16:08:37.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992748/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992748/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Shops: Crimes against the Person","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many assaults against shop keepers were recorded by her Department in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","182146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992749","Home Office","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Home Office collects data on the number of crimes recorded by the police in England and Wales but it is not possible to separately identify assaults against shopkeepers or robberies of shops from the data centrally held.</p><p>Statistics on all assaults and of robberies of business property are published quarterly by the Office for National Statistics (ONS). The latest figures, which contain time series from April 2002 to June 2018, can be accessed here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/datasets/crimeinenglandandwalesappendixtables</a></p><p>The Home Office’s Commercial Victimisation Survey provides estimates of the volume of crime experienced by business premises including in the Wholesale and Retail sector. The survey is able to estimate the number of assaults and threats and the number of robberies experienced by businesses in that sector but the sample size is not large enough to provide separate estimates of the number of assaults against shopkeepers or the proportion of robberies in which a weapon has been used. The latest results from the CVS can be accessed here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/crime-against-businesses-findings-from-the-2017-commercial-victimisation-survey</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","182146","2018-10-25T16:08:37.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992749/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992749/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-22","Shops: Robbery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many and what proportion of robberies of shops recorded by her Department involved the use of a weapon, in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","182147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992750","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-25","<p>As at September 2018, the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy currently has 3583 Permanent staff, 158 Fixed Term Appointment as per payroll returns (exc. Loan/secondments/Faststreamers) and 83 agency temps and contractor staff. Figures based on Headcount not FTE.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-10-25T13:51:59.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992750/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992750/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992750/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-22","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many staff working in his Department are on (a) permanent, (b) fixed-term and (c) causal outsourced contracts.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","182267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992751","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-10-25","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) has the following 15 service categories which are sub-contracted to private providers:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>Security</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>Catering</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>Facilities Management</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>Professional Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>Provision of Technical Advisory Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>Managed Print Service</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>IT Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>Fixed and Mobile Telephony Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>Provision of Legal Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>Shared Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>Provision of Gas Meter and Electricity Meter Testing Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>Call Centre Provision</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>Smart Metering Engineering Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>Regulatory Design Services</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>Business Support Services</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-10-25T13:52:38.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992751/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/992751/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-22","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Contracts for Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and which services in his departmental are sub-contracted to private providers.","false","